News
----
23 Nov 2016 Africa: Doctors in US, Africa work to contain future Ebola outbreaks
http://allafrica.com/stories/201611230639.html
[According to Dr Barb Marston of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, director of the CDC's office for Ebola-affected countries: "Our biggest focus in those 3 countries is on activities related to surveillance, laboratories and building human capacity. ... Right now, we have a team of between 50 and 60; that's counting Americans who are permanently stationed in the 3 countries plus some locally employed staff and also some staff [from] CDC traveling there temporarily to assist."
This kind of cooperation has proven to be helpful in dealing with the latest minor outbreaks, says CDC's Liberia country director, Dr Desmond Williams. "In March, we had a case again in a remote part in Guinea. One of the contacts from that family moved down to the capital city of Liberia, Monrovia," Dr Williams said. "But because the 2 governments were ready this time, we were able to limit that outbreak to 13 infected people and 9 people dead."
Dr Williams told VOA [Voice of America] that the agency's field epidemiology program has trained significant numbers of surveillance officers in Liberia, at the national, county and district levels, but the most important work has been developing laboratory capacity, so health care workers are able to diagnose [Ebola virus disease, EVD] infections rapidly...]

[Building laboratories and increasing human capacity on top of good surveillance is a strong public health approach. A lot has been learned, and a lot of training has taken place. If this can be sustained, rapid response to emergence of Ebola and other hemorrhagic viruses should go a long way to controlling virus transmission. - Mod.LK]

See video:
